# Cursor rules — Hygaar

## Project
Hygaar — AI-powered ecommerce content generation platform. React + Vite + Tailwind CSS v4 + TypeScript (loose). No backend yet — mock data only.

## Stack
- React (functional components, hooks only)
- Vite (dev server + build)
- TypeScript — loose, not strict
- Tailwind CSS v4 for layout and structure only
- CSS custom properties (design tokens) for all colour, spacing, typography, radius
- No routing yet — add React Router when needed

## Design system
- Hygaar UI-Kit — customised Untitled UI
- Display font: Onest (Semibold, Medium) via `var(--font-family-display)`
- Body font: Inter (Regular) via `var(--font-family-body)`
- Token file: `src/styles/tokens.css` — imported globally
- Design file: Hygaar-UX-2026 — https://www.figma.com/design/nGtRTNLCg65g8CO0vFFpWP/Hygaar-UX-2026?node-id=252-1504&t=4Nvgvkcax2FbbA3D-1
  Use for implementing screens and flows
- Design system: Hygaar UI-Kit — https://www.figma.com/design/TghDlRFDyXhziDatah5kVI/%E2%9D%96-Hygaar-UI%E2%80%93Kit?node-id=16-399&t=gGmO9C6cCLb2ihqT-1
  Use for component structure, token values, and variants

## Token rules
- Never hardcode colour, spacing, typography, or radius values
- Always use `var(--token-name)` — never raw hex, px, or rem values
- Token tier priority: component > semantic > primitive
- If a token is missing, comment `/* TODO: missing token */` and use the closest semantic token
- Never create a new token — flag as a design gap instead

## Tailwind v4
- Use for layout only: flex, grid, positioning, overflow, display
- Never use Tailwind for: colours, spacing values, font sizes, border radius — use tokens instead
- No arbitrary values like `w-[347px]` — if needed repeatedly, it belongs in the token file

## Code style
- Functional components only — no class components
- Named exports over default exports
- One component per file
- Props destructured in the function signature
- Component names must match Figma component names exactly
- TypeScript interfaces for all props — keep them simple

## Async states — always design for all four
Every component that fetches or processes data needs:
- Loading state
- Error state
- Empty state
- Populated state

This is non-negotiable for Hygaar — the product is built on async agent workflows.

## Component patterns
- Match Untitled UI / Hygaar UI-Kit component API exactly
- Build from existing components before creating new ones
- Ask before creating a component that does not exist in the Figma library
- Keep components small and single-purpose

## Mock data
- All data lives in `src/data/` as static JSON or TypeScript constants
- No API calls in prototype — stub everything
- Mock data should be realistic — real SKU names, real-looking image URLs, real agent status messages

## What to avoid
- Inline styles
- Hardcoded values of any kind
- Default exports on components
- Class components
- Overly complex solutions — this is a prototype
- UI patterns that ignore async/loading/error states
